n": 740, "end": 747}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9837749004364014, "span": {"begin": 757, "end": 761}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T-cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9159243106842041, "span": {"begin": 850, "end": 857}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:84618"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CNI", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8833722472190857, "span": {"begin": 941, "end": 944}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "B cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9082661271095276, "span": {"begin": 962, "end": 969}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3560"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IL-2 receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9946110844612122, "span": {"begin": 1016, "end": 1030}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NKT cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.8706047534942627, "span": {"begin": 1054, "end": 1063}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4934"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CN", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1105, "end": 1107}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9943278431892395, "span": {"begin": 1108, "end": 1112}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3559"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-2R", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9971522092819214, "span": {"begin": 1246, "end": 1251}}], "text": "As has been mentioned, NFAT has NLS and NES domains among and adjacent to the N-terminal region rich in SP motifs, and once the SP region is dephosphorylated, the NLS domain is exposed whereas the NES doman is covered, which leads to translocation of NFAT into the nucleus (Matsuda and Koyasu 2000).  It is well known from the experiments using CN inhibitors (CNIs) that interference with the nuclear localization of NFAT in T cells leads to a reduction in the formation of NFAT/AP-1 complexes, thereby suppressing transcription of IL-2, IL-4, and a number of other cytokines (Maguire et al. 2013, Jain et al. 1992, Jain et al. 1993).  In contrast to T cells, B-cell receptor-mediated increases in intracellular concentration of calcium in B cells leads to NFAT nuclear localization, thereby producing some classes of cytokines in the same manner as T-cells (Bhattacharyya et al.2011). However, there has been no report of any evidence that CNI acts directly on B cells to effect antibody production.  Expression of IL-2 receptors in dendritic cells and NKT cells is also reported to be regulated by this CN-NFAT system (Panhans-Gross A et al. 2001; Kim et al. 2010), but there is no report showing that CNIs suppress TDAR through the changes in IL-2R expression in these cells.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:54:18 +0000 2026"}